
  GfxLib Utilities / pixeltest

  Name  : pixeltest

  Spec  : 68040/FPU, AmigaOS 3.x, CyberGfx 4.2

  Short : Tests the speed of VRAM access and GfxLib pixel conversion routines.
          Conversion is from a specified source format to whatever format
          the display on which the test window opens is using. Drawing is done
          to an offscreen buffer.

  Notes : DOES NOT WORK ON 8-BIT SCREENS

  Usage : pixeltest [width <num>] [height <num>] [fmt <format>] [-sysdebug]

          width     : width of window (160 - 1024)
          height    : height of window (120 - 768)

          fmt       : source data format, any one of the following pixel types
                      (15-bit)  RGB15B,  RGB15L,  BGR15B,  BGR15L,
                      (16-bit)  RGB16B,  RGB16L,  BGR16B,  BRG16L,
                      (24-bit)  RGB24P,  BGR24P,
                      (32-bit)  ARGB32B, ARGB32L, ABGR16B, ABRG16L

          -sysdebug : enables library debug output

  Detail:

       Set test

       Uses Mem::set()/set16()/set32(). These use 32-bit, aligned writes for
       the largest 32-bit aligned block in the area written to, 16-bit or
       8-bit writes (depending on method) are used for any non 32-bit aligned
       leading / trailing addresses.


       Zero test

       Uses Mem::zero(). This method uses 32-bit aligned writes for the largest
       32-bit aligned block in the area cleared. 8-bit writes are used for
       any non 32-bit leading / trailing addresses.


       Copy test

       Uses Mem::copy(). This method uses 32-bit aligned moves for the
       largest 32-bit aligned blocks in the area copied. 8-bit moves are used
       for any non 32-bit leading / trailing addresses. When source and
       destination are misaligned with respect to one another, exec/CopyMem()
       is used. Note : Overlapping blocks are not supported.


       Conv test

       Uses Gfx2D::getConversion() to get the appropriate pixel conversion
       routine (a function pointer) for the specified ource and destination
       formats. Currently, only copy/byteswap conversions are optimised as
       they use Mem::copy()/Mem::swap().



  GfxLib Utilities / drawtest


  Name  : drawtest

  Spec  : 68040/FPU, AmigaOS 3.x, CyberGfx 4.2, Warp3D 4.2

  Short : Tests the speed of the Rasterizer mesh drawing methods (and hence the
          underlying 3D driver performace) Drawing is done to an offscreen buffer.

  Notes : DOES NOT WORK ON 8-BIT SCREENS

  Usage : drawtest [width <num>] [flat] [cull] [zbuff] [-sysdebug]

          width     : width of window (160 - 1024)
          height    : height of window (120 - 768)

          cull      : cull all polygons, for testing polygon setup speed
          flat      : use flat shading
          zbuff     : use z buffer test / update

          -sysdebug : enables library debug output

  Detail:

          A series of window-filling meshes from 16x16 to 128x128 are calculated
          and rendered using the Rasterizer mesh drawing methods. Two methods
          exist:

          drawTriMesh()  - renders the mesh as a series of unique triangles
          drawTriMesh2() - renders the mesh as a series of triangle strips

          The time interval measured is for the actual drawing stage only. The
          impact that culling, shading and z buffering have can be inspected
          using the optional cull, flat and zbuff arguments



